name: Woman of the Hour
summary: These headlines all refer to a new Netflix film titled "Woman of the Hour," which is based on the true story of Rodney Alcala, a serial killer who was featured on the popular dating show "The Dating Game" in 1978. Alcala's appearance on the show led to his arrest for the murder of several women, and he was eventually convicted of seven counts of murder and sentenced to death. The film, which stars Anna Kendrick as the woman who went on a date with Alcala, explores the chilling details of his crimes and the public fascination with his case. Despite its promising subject matter, some critics have found the film to be dry and academic, while others have praised Kendrick's performance and the film's ability to capture the haunting nature of Alcala's crimes.

name: Oakland Fire
summary: A wildfire in Oakland Hills, California, known as the Keller Fire, has resulted in the evacuation of residents and the spread of the blaze to nearby homes. Gusty conditions have fueled the fire, which is currently 35% contained. Firefighters continue to monitor wind patterns as they work to extinguish the fire. Two homes have been confirmed damaged by the flames, and officials have advised residents to evacuate immediately. The fire has prompted the closure of I-580 but the roadway has since reopened. Forward progress on the fire has been stopped, but crews remain vigilant in case of any change in conditions.

name: Brothers
summary: The Menendez brothers, convicted of murdering their parents in 1989, are seeking resentencing and possible release from prison. Their relatives are rallying outside a Los Angeles courthouse, urging the District Attorney (DA) to consider a shorter sentence. The DA has shared evidence in the case as he weighs the brothers' request. The brothers' uncle, however, opposes their release, dismissing their claims of molestation. In other news, brothers Nick, Kevin, and Joe Jonas, who form the musical group the Jonas Brothers, have built a successful nightlife empire in Washington, D.C. The recent edition of "The View" discussed the Menendez brothers' case, touching on the lasting trauma of childhood scars. Finally, an update in the Menendez brothers' case has been given by the Los Angeles DA, leaving the question of their release unresolved.
